    18	
    19	The instinct is good, but the audit categories are muddled.
    20	
    21	- The chain mixes true symmetries with bookkeeping conventions. `rescaling` is not a harmless cosmetic move unless the full NS scaling, including time and viscosity normalization, is specified. `conjugate completion` is not cosmetic either; for real-valued velocity fields it changes what the packet literally is. `packet regrouping` can change nonlinear bookkeeping in a way that is mathematically substantive, not merely presentational.
    22	- Because those transformations are not cleanly separated, this step may reject a useful definition for failing an invalid invariance requirement.
    23	- The opposite error is also possible: a bad definition can be made "invariant" only because the audit is performed at too abstract a level, before the exact interaction law is written down.
    24	- `helical basis choice` is especially slippery here. If the definition is attached to exact mode interactions, basis dependence may reflect a bad representation choice that should be fixed by canonicalization, not a reason to kill the object entirely.
    25	- The stable/unstable/conditionally stable table is too coarse. Many workable mathematical objects are only stable after choosing a canonical representation. That is not ideal, but it is not obviously fatal for theorem use.
    26	
    27	Net: Step 2 risks enforcing a stronger standard than the mission requires. The mission needs a concrete, testable object, not necessarily a fully coordinate-free ontology.
    28	
    29	## Step 3 - Audit dynamical testability on small exact packets
    30	
    31	This is where the chain's kill calibration becomes suspect.
    32	
    33	- The mission wants a theorem object or a counterexample, not necessarily an object decidable on the tiniest exact packet. Forcing "small exact packet" testability may kill the right definition simply because the phenomenon is inherently multiscale.
    34	- Requiring a finite interaction table or finite leakage metric biases the search toward toy notions. A serious exact-NS obstruction may only emerge for a family of packets or a scale-separated construction.
    35	- The phrase "without hidden asymptotic limits" is fair as an anti-handwaving check, but too absolute. Some asymptotic family may be the only honest way to state near-closure quantitatively.
    36	- A delayed-threshold mechanism is specifically time-sensitive. If the chain refuses any definition that needs a nontrivial finite time horizon or a parameter family, it may rule out the most Tao-relevant formulations by design.
    37	- The expected output is just a memo about what data one would need. That is weak evidence. Almost any candidate can generate a memo; the hard part is whether the required data are robustly accessible and not hypersensitive to tiny trigger modes.
    38	
    39	Net: Step 3 can turn a scope-management convenience into a fake theorem-level veto.
    40	
    41	## Step 4 - Attack the survivors with adversarial edge cases
    42	
    43	This is the strongest step in spirit, but even here the chain is biased.
    44	
    45	- The listed edge cases all come from the inherited non-isolability narrative: Beltrami cancellation, mirror-mode completion, near-degenerate triads, tiny trigger modes. Those are relevant, but they are not a balanced adversarial set.
    46	- Missing are edge cases favorable to the opposite conclusion: carefully engineered helical sign patterns, scale-separated packets, sparse triad geometries, or constructions where leakage is present but dynamically negligible. Without those, the audit is not an attack on the definition space; it is mostly an attack on definitions that do not already agree with the prior mission's intuition.
    47	- The phrase "obviously irrelevant" versus "obviously relevant" is question-begging. Those judgments are exactly what the definition is supposed to settle. If the chain uses inherited intuition as ground truth, it bakes in the desired answer.
    48	- Pass/fail outcomes will depend heavily on threshold choices introduced in Step 1. If those thresholds are not fixed quantitatively first, this step becomes a rhetoric contest.
    49	- Some of these edge cases are not mere boundary tests; they may force a redefinition of the object. The chain treats failure on any one of them as mostly eliminative, which is too brittle.
    50	
    51	Net: Step 4 is useful only if it includes pro-near-circuit stress tests and uses precommitted quantitative criteria.
    52	
    53	## Step 5 - Freeze the mission object or kill it cleanly
    54	
    55	This step is too binary for the state of the problem.
    56	
    57	- A single surviving definition does not imply there is one canonical mission object. Different downstream routes may legitimately need different notions: one leakage-based for obstruction work, one behavioral for adversarial construction work.
    58	- Freezing one definition for "Chains 01-03" is also coordination-sloppy in this run. The selected portfolio is indexed differently, so the handoff target is ambiguous. More importantly, the chain is trying to impose one global object on downstream work before downstream work has tested which notion is actually productive.
    59	- The final kill condition only flags one kind of circularity: hard-coding Tao's averaged construction back into exact NS language. But circularity can also enter through tuned thresholds, cherry-picked time windows, or choosing a packet representation that predetermines leakage.
    60	- The step treats "none survive" as clean evidence that the mission fails at definition level. That conclusion is too strong if the survivors were filtered through the overly aggressive audits in Steps 2-4.
    61	
    62	Net: Step 5 converts earlier methodological choices into a terminal mission verdict too quickly.
    63	
    64	## Structural Weaknesses of the Whole Chain
    65	
    66	- The chain claims to be distinct from theorem work, but it is not. Invariance, testability, and edge-case audits all depend on concrete exact-NS interaction structure. Doing them before a serious exact interaction analysis is backwards.
    67	- The ordering is likely wrong. Definitions and exact packet calculations should co-evolve. Here the chain tries to stabilize the object in abstraction before enough contact with the exact triadic law. That is a recipe for false negatives.
    68	- The chain is structurally biased toward a definition-level kill. Every major step is eliminative, and there is no comparably strong constructive loop that says how a candidate gets improved rather than discarded.
    69	- The success criterion is underspecified, while the kill criteria are relatively sharp. That asymmetry creates predetermined pessimism.
    70	- The chain overstates the need for representation invariance. For this mission, a theorem object may be perfectly acceptable if it is tied to a canonical Fourier/helical presentation. Full robustness under all regroupings is a luxury standard, not obviously the right one.
    71	- There is substantial overlap with the mission brief itself. The mission already says "define the object quantitatively or kill it." This chain adds an audit layer, but not a clearly independent line of attack on the mathematics.
    72	- The chain never cleanly separates three different questions:
    73	  1. Is the object well-defined?
    74	  2. Is the object representation-robust?
    75	  3. Is the object useful for proving anything?
    76	
    77	  Those are related, but they are not the same. The chain too readily treats failure of one as failure of all three.
    78	
    79	## Fair Bottom Line
    80	
    81	If this chain is used, it should not be the sole gatekeeper. Its strongest contribution is to punish circular, threshold-gerrymandered definitions. Its weakest feature is that it can mistake "not yet canonically phrased" for "mathematically nonexistent." As written, it is valuable as an adversarial side-audit, but too brittle and too meta to deserve unilateral authority over whether the mission object is real.
